1
00:00:16,808 --> 00:00:19,560
晚上好，欢迎收看《卡尔佩珀分钟》。
Good evening, and welcome to The Culpeper Minute.

2
00:00:25,567 --> 00:00:26,942
距离那本畅销自传《兜帽之下》揭露初代蒙面冒险家团队——
It's been nearly a decade. . .

3
00:00:27,110 --> 00:00:29,945
——新生民兵的秘密，已过去近十年时光。
...since the best-selling autobiography Under the Hood...

4
00:00:30,113 --> 00:00:33,282
1975年，《卡尔佩珀分钟》首度登陆广播频道时……
...revealed secrets of the original band of masked adventurers...

5
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:35,451
……我们曾专访《兜帽之下》的作者霍利斯·梅森……
...the new Minutemen.

6
00:00:35,744 --> 00:00:38,996
……那位以"夜枭"之名闻名的前冒险家。
In 1975, when The Culpeper Minute was new to the airwaves...

7
00:00:39,164 --> 00:00:42,041
当我的原始报道在1975年播出时，《基恩法案》尚未通过。
. . .we profiled the author of Under the Hood, Hollis Mason. . .

8
00:00:42,208 --> 00:00:44,918
如今，这项颇具争议的法案已将一切变装冒险家与蒙面英雄定为非法。
...the former adventurer known as Nite Owl.

9
00:00:45,086 --> 00:00:49,798
鉴于当前社会对蒙面正义议题的动荡氛围……
When my original report aired in 1 975, the Keene Act had not yet been passed.

10
00:00:49,966 --> 00:00:54,136
……我们认为重温当年那期节目会颇具深意……
Now, this controversial bill outlawed all costumed adventurers and masked heroes.

11
00:00:54,721 --> 00:00:58,599
……以此提醒人们这场变装英雄现象的……
Given our current climate of unrest around the subject of masked justice...

12
00:00:58,767 --> 00:01:02,603
……起源之地。
...we thought it would be interesting to revisit that original episode...

13
00:01:02,771 --> 00:01:05,314
今晚我们将与霍利斯·梅森畅谈他的自传《兜帽之下》。
. . .as a reminder of where the whole phenomena. . .

14
00:01:05,482 --> 00:01:07,983
霍利斯·梅森的回忆录揭示了蒙面冒险家们……
...of costumed heroics began.

15
00:01:13,156 --> 00:01:17,701
……不为人知的秘密。
Tonight we're talking with Hollis Mason about his autobiography, Under the Hood.

16
00:01:17,869 --> 00:01:20,621
Hollis Mason's memoirs revealed some of the secrets...
Hollis Mason's memoirs revealed some of the secrets...

17
00:01:20,789 --> 00:01:22,122
...of the masked adventurers.
...of the masked adventurers.

18
00:01:22,499 --> 00:01:28,170
我在霍利斯最喜欢的纽约餐厅之一——恒河餐厅与他见面。  
I met with Hollis at one of his favorite New York establishments, the Gunga Diner.

19
00:01:30,673 --> 00:01:32,800
十二岁来到纽约……  
Coming to New York at 1 2 years old...

20
00:01:32,967 --> 00:01:37,513
……在很多方面，这对我来说，呃，都棒极了。  
...it was, uh, fantastic for me in a lot of ways.

21
00:01:38,306 --> 00:01:42,643
我父亲在第七大道旁的弗农汽车修理店找到了一份工作。  
And my dad got a job at Vernon's Auto Repair off 7th Avenue.

22
00:01:42,977 --> 00:01:46,146
-现在是梅森汽修，对吧？ -现在是梅森汽修。对，对。  
-Now Mason's, right? -Now Mason's. Yeah, yeah.

23
00:01:46,564 --> 00:01:47,648
同一个地方。  
Same place.

24
00:01:47,816 --> 00:01:51,193
卡尔佩珀：但你并没有追随父亲的脚步。你选择了另一条路。  
CULPEPER: Yet you didn't follow in your father's footsteps. You chose another path.

25
00:01:51,361 --> 00:01:53,445
梅森：嗯，是的，当我二十三岁时……  
MASON: Well, yeah, when l was 23...

26
00:01:54,197 --> 00:01:57,324
……我加入了纽约市警察局。  
...l joined the New York City Police Department.

27
00:01:57,492 --> 00:02:01,120
我认为这很大程度上与我祖父有关……  
And l think that that had a lot to do with my grandfather...

28
00:02:01,287 --> 00:02:04,164
……以及他灌输给我的价值观。  
...and the values that he'd instilled in me.

29
00:02:04,332 --> 00:02:08,127
因为在我人生的前十二年，我大部分时间都和祖父在一起。  
Because for the first 1 2 years of my life, I spent a lot of time with my granddad.

30
00:02:08,294 --> 00:02:11,296
他总是热衷于让我铭记……  
He was always keen to impress upon me...

31
00:02:11,464 --> 00:02:18,011
……乡下人在道德上比城里人更健康，这是他们的生活方式。  
...that country folk were morally healthier than city folk, the way they lived.

32
00:02:18,179 --> 00:02:21,640
当然，在某些方面你们会相互竞争，但你们也——  
Of course you were competitive in certain ways, but you were also--

33
00:02:21,808 --> 00:02:22,975
你们会互相帮助。  
You helped each other.

34
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:26,895
这是一种深深印在我心中的道德价值观。  
And it was kind of a moral value that stuck with me.

35
00:02:27,063 --> 00:02:29,731
当我初到这座城市时……
And when I first got to the city...

36
00:02:29,899 --> 00:02:35,279
...我目睹的一些事 真的让我感到恶心...
...there were things l saw that really filled me with disgust...

37
00:02:35,446 --> 00:02:40,284
...我很难摆脱 而且 你知道 有些真的——
...that l found a hard time shaking, and, you know, some really--

38
00:02:40,743 --> 00:02:43,078
有些我至今仍无法释怀。
Some of it l still can't.

39
00:02:54,340 --> 00:02:57,384
我祖父教给我的...
What my grandfather gave me...

40
00:02:57,552 --> 00:03:00,304
...以及我在城市里所面对的——
...and what I was confronted with in the city--

41
00:03:00,471 --> 00:03:04,391
当这两者之间的差距太大 我无法承受时...
When the distance between those things got too great and I couldn't deal with it...

42
00:03:04,559 --> 00:03:09,771
...我就会逃往我真正的另一个世界 通俗小说的世界。
...then l would go to my real other world, the world of pulp-fiction novels.

43
00:03:11,941 --> 00:03:15,485
它们描绘了一个绝对价值的世界...
They described a world of absolute values...

44
00:03:15,653 --> 00:03:18,614
...在那里 善与真从不被质疑。
...where what was good and true was never in doubt.

45
00:03:18,781 --> 00:03:20,616
而恶——
And evil was--

46
00:03:20,783 --> 00:03:24,411
嗯 它总会得到应有的惩罚。
Well, it received its appropriate punishment.

47
00:03:24,579 --> 00:03:26,705
那么 你就是这样度过一生的吗？
Is that how you've led your life, then?

48
00:03:26,873 --> 00:03:30,250
-我一直努力这么做 嗯... -嗯。
-That's what I've tried to do. Um.... -Mm-hm.

49
00:03:31,628 --> 00:03:32,920
是的。
Yeah.

50
00:03:33,087 --> 00:03:35,631
霍利斯·梅森 理想主义的年轻警察...
Hollis Mason, idealizing young cop...

51
00:03:35,798 --> 00:03:38,592
...试图理解祖父的乡村价值观...
...trying to make sense of granddad's country values...

52
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:41,637
...与他所生活的大都市的残酷现实。
...and the grit of the big city he finds himself living in.

53
00:03:41,804 --> 00:03:46,433
很快 警队及其正义品牌对年轻的梅森来说已不够。
Soon enough, the police force and its brand ofjustice is not enough for young Mason.

54
00:03:46,601 --> 00:03:50,646
长久以来痴迷于侦探通俗小说和漫画英雄主义...
Long a fan of pulp detective fiction and comic-book heroics...

55
00:03:50,813 --> 00:03:53,315
...梅森做了别人只敢幻想的事。
...Mason did what others only fantasize about.

56
00:03:53,483 --> 00:03:54,983
他为自己做了伪装……
He made himself a disguise...

57
00:03:55,151 --> 00:03:57,903
……在夜晚以义警的身份出动……
...and set out in the nights as a vigilante...

58
00:03:58,071 --> 00:04:00,614
……按照自己的方式伸张正义。
...doling out justice on his own terms.

59
00:04:00,782 --> 00:04:04,326
是什么影响了梅森行为的转变？
What influenced this shift in Mason's behavior?

60
00:04:05,995 --> 00:04:07,871
想想还挺有趣的。
It's funny when you think about it.

61
00:04:09,958 --> 00:04:12,125
你知道，我听过所有的——
You know, I've heard all the--

62
00:04:12,293 --> 00:04:15,504
所有的笑话、所有的谣言和所有的影射。
All the jokes and all the rumors and all the innuendos.

63
00:04:15,713 --> 00:04:18,507
对我来说，真正重要的是……
What it really comes down to for me...

64
00:04:18,675 --> 00:04:22,344
……是我打扮成猫头鹰打击犯罪……
...is that l dressed up like an owl and l fought crime...

65
00:04:24,305 --> 00:04:26,306
……因为那很有趣。
...because it was fun.

66
00:04:26,891 --> 00:04:29,351
也因为那是正确的事。
And because it was the right thing to do.

67
00:04:30,270 --> 00:04:32,980
还因为我确实乐在其中。
And because l darn well enjoyed it.

68
00:04:33,606 --> 00:04:34,940
[梅森轻笑]
[MASON CHUCKLES]

69
00:04:35,108 --> 00:04:40,028
我想这一切对我来说真正开始成形是在1938年。
I suppose it really started to take shape for me in 1 938.

70
00:04:40,196 --> 00:04:45,909
在我的巡逻区域，有很多孩子在读《动作漫画》的第一期。
And on my beat there were a lot of kids reading that first issue of Action Comics.

71
00:04:46,077 --> 00:04:48,287
我被深深吸引，无法自拔。
I was so drawn, I couldn't help it.

72
00:04:48,454 --> 00:04:51,540
我问其中一个孩子能否借来看看。
I asked one of the kids if l could borrow it and take a look at it.

73
00:04:51,708 --> 00:04:55,252
而《超人》的第一期……
And that first issue of Superman...

74
00:04:55,712 --> 00:04:58,380
-……哇，让我震撼不已。-嗯。
-...wow, knocked me out. -Mm-hm.

75
00:04:59,007 --> 00:05:03,302
好吧，超人对你影响最大，对很多孩子也是如此。
Okay, Superman was your biggest influence, and it was to a lot of kids.

76
00:05:03,469 --> 00:05:05,846
但你走得更远。
But you took it even further.

77
00:05:06,014 --> 00:05:09,558
梅森：嗯，一切都在我有一天翻开报纸时改变了……
MASON: Well, it all changed when l opened the newspaper one day...

78
00:05:09,726 --> 00:05:15,689
……我看到这些角色从他们四色的世界中逃离出来……
...and l saw that these characters had escaped from their four-color world...

79
00:05:15,857 --> 00:05:22,154
……他们现在身处报纸头条那真实的黑白世界里。
...and they were now in the factual black-and-white world of the headlines.

80
00:05:24,615 --> 00:05:28,535
一次企图袭击和抢劫的事件被一个身影阻止了……
An attempted assault and robbery was thwarted by a figure...

81
00:05:28,703 --> 00:05:31,830
……据说他是从上方跳入小巷的……
...who supposedly dropped into the alleyway from above...

82
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:33,749
……脸上蒙着东西。
...with something over his face.

83
00:05:33,916 --> 00:05:37,252
然后他解除了三名袭击者的武装……
And he then proceeded to disarm the three attackers...

84
00:05:37,420 --> 00:05:41,465
……并狠狠地殴打了他们，导致三人全部住院。
...and beat them with such severity that all three were hospitalized.

85
00:05:41,632 --> 00:05:45,719
报纸开始称他为“兜帽判官”。
The newspapers started calling him Hooded Justice.

86
00:05:45,887 --> 00:05:50,474
而那就是第一位蒙面义警。
And that was the first masked vigilante.

87
00:05:50,850 --> 00:05:54,853
当我听到那个故事时，我立刻下定决心……
And when I heard that story I made up my mind right then...

88
00:05:55,021 --> 00:05:58,690
……我要成为第二个。
...l was gonna be the second.

89
00:05:58,858 --> 00:06:02,110
我们现在需要为赞助商休息一下，但当我们回来时……
We have to take a break for our sponsors now, but when we come back...

90
00:06:02,278 --> 00:06:06,573
……我们将继续讲述1975年关于蒙面冒险家的故事。
...more from our 1 975 story on masked adventurers.

91
00:06:39,273 --> 00:06:40,899
感谢您继续收听。
Thank you for staying with us.

92
00:06:41,067 --> 00:06:44,277
我们现在回到对《兜帽之下》的回顾……
We return now to our retrospective look at Under the Hood...

93
00:06:44,445 --> 00:06:47,489
……以及这些男男女女对我们今天的意义。
...and what these men and women mean to us today.

94
00:06:49,033 --> 00:06:51,535
卡尔佩珀：你为什么想到设计猫头鹰服装？
CULPEPER: Why did you come up with the owl costume?

95
00:06:51,702 --> 00:06:53,620
梅森：它真的是自然而然形成的……
MASON: It really came together...

96
00:06:53,788 --> 00:06:57,707
...因为局里和我共事的另一个警察。
...because of another cop that l was working with in my station house.

97
00:06:57,875 --> 00:07:01,086
他总在问下班后要不要一起去喝一杯。
And he kept asking me to go out for a beer after work.

98
00:07:01,254 --> 00:07:05,132
而我总在拒绝，因为，你知道，我晚上要训练...
And l kept saying no, because, you know, I wanted to train at night...

99
00:07:05,299 --> 00:07:07,300
...为我另一份事业做准备。
...and get ready for my other career.

100
00:07:07,468 --> 00:07:10,137
然后他就开始叫我"夜猫子"。
And then he started calling me "night owl."

101
00:07:10,304 --> 00:07:13,140
-你知道，他是在挖苦我。-没错。
-You know, he was being sarcastic. -Right.

102
00:07:13,307 --> 00:07:17,769
但我很喜欢。我想，"好吧，就叫夜猫子吧。"
And l loved it. I thought, "Well, that's it, Nite Owl."

103
00:07:17,937 --> 00:07:20,605
-所以名字就是这么来的？-就是这么来的。
-So that's where the name came from? -That's where it came from.

104
00:07:20,773 --> 00:07:24,067
有了名字后，我就开始构思服装。
So once l had the name, then I could start thinking about the costume.

105
00:07:24,235 --> 00:07:28,864
该不该有披风？该不该戴面具？
Should it have a cape or no cape? Should you have a mask or no mask?

106
00:07:29,031 --> 00:07:31,741
最终，我把它精简到了最基本的要素。
Eventually, l just boiled it down to the basics.

107
00:07:31,909 --> 00:07:33,910
我需要一套能自由活动的服装。
I needed a costume where l was free to move.

108
00:07:34,078 --> 00:07:36,746
我需要保护身体。我需要保护头部。
I needed to protect my body. I needed to protect my head.

109
00:07:36,914 --> 00:07:39,499
我还需要隐藏身份。
And l needed to protect my identity.

110
00:07:39,667 --> 00:07:44,838
所以我做了这件覆盖着皮革和锁子甲的上衣...
So l did this with a tunic that was covered in leather and mail...

111
00:07:45,006 --> 00:07:46,465
...一种钢制网眼。
...a kind of steel mesh.

112
00:07:46,632 --> 00:07:51,595
我还有个头罩——同样是皮革和钢网制成的。
And l had a hood with-- It was leather and steel mesh again.

113
00:07:51,762 --> 00:07:55,557
然后是短裤。也覆盖着同样的锁子甲。
And then briefs. They were covered in the same mail.

114
00:07:55,725 --> 00:07:59,186
所以我把头发遮起来，只需要一个小面具。
So l've got my hair covered and all l need is a little mask.

115
00:07:59,353 --> 00:08:01,813
于是我用这个做了面具，就是这个面具。
So l did it with this. This is the mask.

116
00:08:01,981 --> 00:08:05,525
我用酒精胶粘上了这个面具……
I attached this mask with a spirit gum...

117
00:08:05,693 --> 00:08:09,571
……就是演员用来贴胡子和假须的那种。
...which is what actors use to put on mustaches and beards.

118
00:08:09,739 --> 00:08:12,741
卡尔佩珀：结果发现，当时有好几个蒙面的冒险者。
CULPEPER: lt turned out, there were several masked adventurers at the time.

119
00:08:12,909 --> 00:08:15,494
梅森：是的，在我首次亮相大约一个月后……
MASON: Yeah, about a month after I made my debut...

120
00:08:15,661 --> 00:08:21,333
……头条新闻都是关于一个叫剪影的年轻女子。
...the headlines were all about a young woman called the Silhouette.

121
00:08:21,501 --> 00:08:26,546
她揭露了一个经营儿童色情制品的奸诈出版商。
She had exposed a crooked publisher who was dealing in child pornography.

122
00:08:26,714 --> 00:08:33,220
她还狠狠地揍了他一顿。他和他的两个摄影师，对吧？
And she gave him such a brutal beating. Him and his two cameramen, right?

123
00:08:33,387 --> 00:08:35,931
嗯，那真是个轰动一时的故事。
Well, that was quite a story.

124
00:08:36,224 --> 00:08:38,433
从那以后，事情发展得相当快。
From there it grew pretty quickly.

125
00:08:44,649 --> 00:08:48,109
有传闻说有个穿得像飞蛾的男人……
There were stories of a man dressed like a moth...

126
00:08:48,277 --> 00:08:51,279
……能在空中滑翔。
...who could glide through the air.

127
00:08:54,909 --> 00:08:59,246
后来又有个故事，讲的是一个穿黄色连体工装服的男人……
And then there was a story of a man in a yellow boiler suit...

128
00:08:59,413 --> 00:09:03,959
……他特别残忍和恶毒。
...who was particularly brutal and vicious.

129
00:09:04,502 --> 00:09:09,631
在兜帽判官戏剧性登场后的12个月里……
In 12 months of Hooded Justice's dramatic entrance...

130
00:09:09,799 --> 00:09:13,510
……至少出现了，哦，其他七个穿戏服的义务警员。
...there were at least, oh, seven other costumed vigilantes.

131
00:09:13,678 --> 00:09:16,972
还有莎莉·朱庇特，她取了丝魂这个名字。
There was Sally Jupiter, who took the name of Silk Spectre.

132
00:09:17,139 --> 00:09:19,307
有美钞比尔，有飞蛾人……
There was Dollar Bill, there was Mothman...

133
00:09:19,475 --> 00:09:21,768
……有剪影侠，有笑匠。
...there was the Silhouette, there was Comedian.

134
00:09:21,936 --> 00:09:24,020
当然，还有我。
And, of course, there was me.

135
00:09:24,814 --> 00:09:27,732
梅森告诉我的事情，大多已写在他的书里。
Little that Mason told me was not already in his book.

136
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:32,737
于是我转向他世界里的其他人物，以了解更多。
So l turned to some of the other figures from his world to find out more.

137
00:09:34,448 --> 00:09:36,992
她利用自己的性感来打击犯罪……
She used her sexuality to fight crime...

138
00:09:37,159 --> 00:09:40,579
……又凭借打击犯罪的经历在银幕上谋求事业。
...and her crime fighting to pursue a career on the silver screen.

139
00:09:40,746 --> 00:09:43,415
如今她的女儿延续着她的形象……
Now her daughter lives on in her image...

140
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:46,543
……而生活似乎已将莎莉·朱庇特抛在身后。
...and life seemingly has passed Sally Jupiter by.

141
00:09:47,128 --> 00:09:51,256
1975年，我们在她家中进行了以下对话。
We joined her at her home for the following exchange back in 1 975.

142
00:09:53,551 --> 00:09:55,844
卡尔佩珀：为何取名丝魂？
CULPEPER: Why the name Silk Spectre?

143
00:09:56,012 --> 00:09:57,220
朱庇特：说来有趣。
JUPITER: You know, it's funny.

144
00:09:57,388 --> 00:10:01,308
很多人猜测过这个名字的由来。
Many people have hypothesized about reasons why that might have come up.

145
00:10:01,475 --> 00:10:05,020
而事实上，我只是想找个神秘的名字……
And in truth, I wanted to find something mysterious...

146
00:10:05,187 --> 00:10:07,188
……听起来顺耳的那种，明白吗？
...something that had a good ring to it, you know?

147
00:10:07,356 --> 00:10:11,860
我觉得她应该是那种能从你指缝中溜走的人物。
And l felt that she should be somebody who could slip out of your hands.

148
00:10:12,028 --> 00:10:15,196
要知道，当时丝袜非常昂贵。
Silk stockings, you know, were very expensive at the time.

149
00:10:15,364 --> 00:10:19,075
我想，这名字确实朗朗上口——我只能这么解释了。
And it just had a good ring to it, l guess, is all I can really say.

150
00:10:19,243 --> 00:10:23,330
你成为蒙面冒险家的动机是什么？
What were your motivations in becoming a masked adventurer?

151
00:10:23,497 --> 00:10:26,041
我看到了兜帽判官……
I saw Hooded Justice...

152
00:10:26,208 --> 00:10:29,711
……我觉得做点不同寻常的事——
...and l think the idea of doing something that was out of the normal--

153
00:10:29,879 --> 00:10:31,588
我从未觉得自己真正融入过。
I never felt like l really fit in.

154
00:10:31,756 --> 00:10:36,718
而成为丝鬼确实让我感觉更像找到了归属。
And l think that becoming Silk Spectre really made me feel actually more at home.

155
00:10:37,219 --> 00:10:42,766
如今，丝鬼在海报和漫画中的形象都相当大胆。
Now, Silk Spectre is presented in fairly racy imagery in posters and in comics.

156
00:10:42,933 --> 00:10:47,646
你如何处理这些我称之为视觉贬低的图片？
How do you deal with these, what I call, visually degrading pictures?

157
00:10:47,813 --> 00:10:50,732
哦，我对那种事从来没什么意见。
Oh, l never had a problem with that sort of thing.

158
00:10:50,900 --> 00:10:54,527
我是说，你知道，他们总把我称作性感符号。
I mean, you know, they always referred to me as a sex symbol.

159
00:10:54,695 --> 00:10:57,030
我得说，我宁愿成为那样的符号……
And l have to say, I'd rather be a symbol of that...

160
00:10:57,198 --> 00:11:00,116
……也不愿成为他们那些其他符号的象征。
...than a symbol for other things they've got symbols of.

161
00:11:00,284 --> 00:11:01,785
你明白我的意思吗？
You know what l mean?

162
00:11:01,952 --> 00:11:05,372
吉米·范图奇，一个著名的黑帮分子，我相信你听说过他。
Jimmy Fantucci, a famous mobster, I'm sure you've heard of him.

163
00:11:05,539 --> 00:11:09,167
他实际上向警方自首了，因为他无法对我开枪。
He actually turned himself into the cops because he couldn't shoot me.

164
00:11:09,335 --> 00:11:13,546
你知道，正如我所说，我从不回避自己的外貌。
You know, as l said, l never shied away from the way that I looked.

165
00:11:13,714 --> 00:11:15,799
而且，事实上，在这种情况下，我似乎可以利用它。
And, in fact, it seemed in this case, I could use it.

166
00:11:15,966 --> 00:11:19,844
蒙面冒险家或随便你们怎么称呼他们本质上都是商业行为。
Masked adventurers or whatever what you wanna call them is all about commerce.

167
00:11:20,012 --> 00:11:24,432
你们必须记住这个国家是建立在娱乐业之上的。
You have to remember that this country was founded on entertainment.

168
00:11:24,600 --> 00:11:27,435
当我管理丝鬼萨莉时……
And when I managed Sally, the Silk Spectre...

169
00:11:27,603 --> 00:11:33,274
……我们利用她作为蒙面英雄的身份达成了各种利润丰厚的交易。
...we used her status as a costumed hero to make lucrative deals of every kind.

170
00:11:33,442 --> 00:11:37,946
电影合约、海报形象授权、漫画书，无所不包。
Movie deals, image licensing for pinups, comic books, everything.

171
00:11:38,114 --> 00:11:42,367
这种商业策略几乎立刻就被各大企业采纳了。
It was a business strategy that corporations picked up on almost immediately.

172
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:45,245
美元比尔原本是堪萨斯州的大学体育明星……
Dollar Bill was originally a star college athlete from Kansas...

173
00:11:45,413 --> 00:11:47,205
……被一家大型百货公司聘用……
...hired by a major department store...

174
00:11:47,373 --> 00:11:49,958
……因为他们意识到拥有自己的超级英雄……
...when they realized that having their own superhero...

175
00:11:50,126 --> 00:11:53,211
……是个颇具前景的宣传策略。
...was an interesting publicity prospect.

176
00:11:53,379 --> 00:11:56,798
不过我还是认为萨莉和我开创了这个概念。
Still, l like to think that Sally and I pioneered the concept.

177
00:11:56,966 --> 00:12:00,218
当你想在世界上留下印记时，你需要帮助。
When you're trying to make a mark in the world, you need help.

178
00:12:00,386 --> 00:12:04,180
你需要一个能起到凝聚作用的人……
You need someone who can be sort of the cohesive factor...

179
00:12:04,348 --> 00:12:08,143
……将这种意识传递给公众，而他确实做到了。
...in bringing the awareness to the public, and he definitely did that.

180
00:12:08,310 --> 00:12:12,021
而且我认为，实际上这可能牺牲了许多人的计划。
And l think, in fact, probably at the expense of many people's agendas, really.

181
00:12:12,189 --> 00:12:14,315
我不认为你能做出价值判断……
I don't think you can make value judgments...

182
00:12:14,483 --> 00:12:18,945
……关于蒙面英雄对社会是好是坏。
...on whether or not costumed heroes are good or bad for society.

183
00:12:19,113 --> 00:12:21,948
这就像问电视是好是坏一样。
That's like asking if television is good or bad.

184
00:12:22,116 --> 00:12:23,950
答案是两者皆有。
The answer is that it's both.

185
00:12:24,118 --> 00:12:28,163
真正的问题始于我们聚在一起之后……
It was only really when we got together...

186
00:12:28,664 --> 00:12:32,584
……问题才真正开始。
...that the problems started.

187
00:12:32,752 --> 00:12:34,919
是的，就是民兵组织。
The Minutemen, yeah.

188
00:12:35,087 --> 00:12:36,421
多棒的主意啊。
What a great idea.

189
00:12:36,589 --> 00:12:41,009
我真希望这功劳能归我，但凭良心说我不能。
I wish I can take credit for it, but I can't in good conscience.

190
00:12:41,177 --> 00:12:46,264
事情是这样的，有一天我收到了大都会队长写给莎莉的信。
The way it happened was one day l got a letter for Sally from Captain Metropolis.

191
00:12:46,432 --> 00:12:48,767
他说他想聚在一起讨论这个想法……
He said he wanted to get together to discuss the idea...

192
00:12:48,934 --> 00:12:51,352
……组建一个蒙面冒险家团体。
...of forming a group of masked adventurers.

193
00:12:51,520 --> 00:12:55,315
起初，我以为他是想用这个主意作为把她弄上床的手段。
At first, I thought he was using the idea as a means to get her into bed.

194
00:12:55,483 --> 00:12:57,358
然后我做了一些调查……
Then l did a little research...

195
00:12:57,526 --> 00:13:00,737
……我了解到我的担忧……
...and l learned that my concerns...

196
00:13:00,905 --> 00:13:04,616
……是的，是没有根据的……
...were, yeah, unfounded...

197
00:13:04,784 --> 00:13:07,911
……如果你明白我的意思的话。
...if you get my meaning.

198
00:13:08,120 --> 00:13:10,663
劳伦斯创建了民兵组织。
Lawrence made the Minutemen.

199
00:13:10,831 --> 00:13:13,833
如果不是因为他和他的宣传天赋——
If it wasn't for him and his knack for publicity--

200
00:13:14,001 --> 00:13:17,962
我想，作为你这一行的人，你大概能理解……
I mean l think as someone in your profession, you could probably understand...

201
00:13:18,130 --> 00:13:21,716
……如果我们做了这次采访却没人看到，那么，噗，一切就都不重要了。
...that if we did this interview and no one saw it, then, poof, it doesn't matter.

202
00:13:21,884 --> 00:13:24,636
谢克奈德：我意识到如果没有偶尔的噱头……
SHEXNAYDER: I realized that without the occasional gimmick...

203
00:13:24,804 --> 00:13:27,138
……来重振日渐衰落的公众兴趣……
...to revitalize flagging public interest...

204
00:13:27,306 --> 00:13:29,974
……这些穿着奇装异服的英雄热潮……
...the fad of costumed heroes...

205
00:13:30,142 --> 00:13:32,894
……最终会逐渐消退，即使是那些打扮得像莎莉的人也不例外。
...would eventually fade, even the ones dressed like Sally.

206
00:13:33,062 --> 00:13:36,731
经过一番考虑，我建议他们在《公报》上刊登一则大幅广告……
After some consideration l suggested they take a large ad out in the Gazette...

207
00:13:36,899 --> 00:13:39,734
……邀请更多神秘人物挺身而出。
...asking for more mystery men to come forward.

208
00:13:39,902 --> 00:13:43,363
这就是"民兵"组织的由来。
And that's how the Minutemen came to be.

209
00:13:44,031 --> 00:13:45,990
卡尔佩珀：那么，当你第一次见到"笑匠"时……
CULPEPER: Now, when you first met The Comedian...

210
00:13:46,158 --> 00:13:48,243
……"夜枭"、"剪影"和其他人……
...Nite Owl, Silhouette and the others...

211
00:13:48,410 --> 00:13:51,788
……你当时有什么想法？你感到害怕吗？
...what were your thoughts? Were you intimidated?

212
00:13:51,956 --> 00:13:53,581
是否有一种如释重负的感觉？
Was there a sense of relief?

213
00:13:53,749 --> 00:13:57,585
哦，我必须说，那是一个令人难以置信的振奋人心的时期。
Oh, it was an incredibly exhilarating time, I have to say.

214
00:13:57,753 --> 00:14:00,922
我想我们都觉得自己是家庭的一部分……
I think we all felt like we were part of a family...

215
00:14:01,090 --> 00:14:03,883
……我们找到了某种归属地……
...that we had found sort of a place...

216
00:14:04,051 --> 00:14:06,678
……在那里我们可以感觉自己确实是有价值的。
...where we could feel like we actually were of value.

217
00:14:06,846 --> 00:14:09,347
每个人都为"民兵"带来了不同的东西。
Everyone brought something different to the Minutemen.

218
00:14:09,515 --> 00:14:12,892
但不知何故，当我们在一起时，有一种团结的感觉……
But somehow when we were together there was a bonding feeling...

219
00:14:13,060 --> 00:14:15,436
……我们都相信我们所做的事情。
...that we all believed in what we were doing.

220
00:14:15,604 --> 00:14:19,691
现在，我之所以说"如释重负"，是因为在那个年代，许多人……
Now, the reason I say "relief" is because many of the people back in those days...

221
00:14:19,859 --> 00:14:23,653
...认为你们都是相当古怪、不正常的人...
...thought that you were all rather bizarre, abnormal individuals...

222
00:14:23,821 --> 00:14:26,739
...穿着儿童服装到处跑。
...running around in children's costumes.

223
00:14:26,907 --> 00:14:28,241
朱庇特：我们只是普通人。
JUPITER: We were just people.

224
00:14:28,409 --> 00:14:31,327
而且每个人的政治立场确实完全不同。
And everyone did have absolutely different politics.

225
00:14:31,495 --> 00:14:34,205
我们中有些人是为了名声。有些人是为了权力。
Some of us were in it for fame. Some for power.

226
00:14:34,373 --> 00:14:38,334
有些人可能是为了躲避这个世界。
Some to possibly hide from the rest of the world.

227
00:14:38,502 --> 00:14:42,505
但归根结底，我们的政治立场并没有太多妨碍...
But in the end of the day, our politics really didn't get in the way too much...

228
00:14:42,673 --> 00:14:45,383
...我们想要在那里做的事情，这是好事。
...of what we wanted to be there to do, which was good.

229
00:14:45,551 --> 00:14:50,430
我们在各自的社区做了太多好事，不能被一笔勾销。
We did too much good in our respective communities just to be written off.

230
00:14:50,598 --> 00:14:53,474
我们都试图通过个人的努力...
We were all attempting through our personal efforts...

231
00:14:53,642 --> 00:14:58,813
...让我们的国家成为一个更好、更安全的居住地。
...to make our country a better and a safer place to live.

232
00:14:58,981 --> 00:15:02,150
显然，霍利斯·梅森是一个对自己的人生...
Clearly, Hollis Mason is a man who makes no apologies...

233
00:15:02,318 --> 00:15:04,903
...或所做的决定毫不后悔的人。
...for the life he's lived or the decisions he's made.

234
00:15:05,070 --> 00:15:08,489
但他个人的道德准则是否足以成为...
But is his own personal moral code enough justification...

235
00:15:08,657 --> 00:15:11,868
...戴上面具、执行私刑正义的理由？
...for donning a mask and dispensing vigilante justice?

236
00:15:12,036 --> 00:15:15,038
我出去四处询问，以更好地了解...
I went out and asked around to get a better sense...

237
00:15:15,205 --> 00:15:18,791
...你们，人民，对蒙面英雄的看法。
...of how you, the people, felt about masked heroes.

238
00:15:25,132 --> 00:15:26,799
男子1：我不知道。
MAN 1 : I don't know.

239
00:15:26,967 --> 00:15:28,843
我这儿有很多顾客是警察。
I get a lot of customers that are cops.

240
00:15:29,011 --> 00:15:31,429
他们常来我这儿买包烟...
Guys that come by and pay for a pack of smokes from me...

241
00:15:31,597 --> 00:15:35,183
...然后告诉我这些蒙面义警...
...and they tell me that these masked adventurers...

242
00:15:35,351 --> 00:15:38,019
...让他们的工作变得更难了。
...they're making the job more difficult.

243
00:15:39,480 --> 00:15:41,147
男子2：我怎么看他们？
MAN 2: What do I think of them?

244
00:15:41,315 --> 00:15:43,858
他们几乎毁了我的生意，我可以这么说。
They've just about destroyed my business, I can tell you that.

245
00:15:45,736 --> 00:15:48,529
他们把我的顾客弄成残废。
They maim my customers.

246
00:15:48,697 --> 00:15:53,159
他们喜欢折断手指。他们觉得这很有趣。是的。他们很危险。
They like to break fingers. They think it's funny. Yeah. They're dangerous.

247
00:15:53,577 --> 00:15:56,245
但另一方面，如果我们没有...
But then on the other hand, what if we hadn't had...

248
00:15:56,413 --> 00:15:59,248
...那个曼哈顿博士站在我们这边，会怎样呢？
...that Dr. Manhattan guy on our side, huh?

249
00:15:59,416 --> 00:16:02,919
我是说，我知道以我们现在所知来看，这难以想象...
I mean, l know it's inconceivable to us, now knowing what we know...

250
00:16:03,212 --> 00:16:06,714
...但谁能说没有他们...
...but who's to say that things wouldn't have gone the same in Vietnam...

251
00:16:06,882 --> 00:16:08,216
...越南的情况就不会一样呢？
...without them?

252
00:16:08,384 --> 00:16:10,093
输掉那场战争。
Losing that war.

253
00:16:10,260 --> 00:16:11,886
那会毁掉我们的国家。
That would've destroyed our country.

254
00:16:13,013 --> 00:16:16,391
更多关于蒙面义警及其引发的争议...
More on costumed adventurers and the controversy surrounding them...

255
00:16:16,558 --> 00:16:19,310
...将在赞助商信息后继续播报。
...after this word from our sponsors.

256
00:16:20,646 --> 00:16:24,941
播报员：精工宣布推出世界首款数字石英液晶计时码表。
ANNOUNCER: Seiko announces the world's first digital quartz, liquid crystal chronograph.

257
00:16:25,109 --> 00:16:26,734
它能显示时间、日期...
lt gives the time, the date...

258
00:16:26,902 --> 00:16:29,529
...并且按下一个按钮，就能变成秒表...
...and with a push of a button, turns into a stopwatch...

259
00:16:29,697 --> 00:16:33,783
...记录着圈速和冠亚军成绩，精确到十分之一秒。  
...that records lap times and one-two finishes in tenths of seconds.

260
00:16:33,951 --> 00:16:38,621
按下按钮，储存在电子记忆中的时间便会再次显现。  
The time of day, kept in electronic memory, reappears when you push the button again.

261
00:16:38,789 --> 00:16:40,915
精工液晶计时码表。  
The Seiko liquid crystal chronograph.

262
00:16:41,083 --> 00:16:44,335
这只是精工卓越数字石英腕表中的一款。  
Only one of Seiko's superb digital quartz watches.

263
00:16:50,801 --> 00:16:53,261
欢迎回来，感谢您的收看。  
Welcome back, and thank you for watching.

264
00:16:53,429 --> 00:16:58,182
在当前环境下，蒙面冒险者——守望者们的现实意义...  
In our current climate, the relevance of masked adventurers, the Watchmen...

265
00:16:58,350 --> 00:17:00,435
...比以往任何时候都更受质疑。  
...is more in question than ever before.

266
00:17:00,602 --> 00:17:02,895
我们现在继续回顾一档节目...  
We continue now with our look back at a show...

267
00:17:03,063 --> 00:17:05,106
...其中我们讨论了《兜帽之下》...  
...in which we discussed Under the Hood...

268
00:17:05,274 --> 00:17:09,944
...一本关于初代蒙面英雄夜枭（原名霍利斯·梅森）的回忆录。  
...a memoir of original masked hero The Nite Owl, née Hollis Mason.

269
00:17:10,112 --> 00:17:13,322
这本书引出了许多我们至今仍在探讨的问题...  
A book which precipitated many of the questions we have today...

270
00:17:13,490 --> 00:17:18,453
...关于这些游离于既定法律之外的男男女女。  
...about these men and women who act apart from our prescribed laws ofjustice.

271
00:17:31,133 --> 00:17:35,762
当然，有许多身着戏服的英雄值得深入研究。  
Certainly there are many costumed heroes who would make for fascinating study.

272
00:17:35,929 --> 00:17:38,556
我曾与精神病学家威廉·朗交谈...  
I spoke with psychiatrist William Long...

273
00:17:38,724 --> 00:17:40,767
...以获取一些专业见解。  
...to gain some professional insight.

274
00:17:40,934 --> 00:17:43,561
您知道，这是个有趣的问题。  
You know, it's an interesting question.

275
00:17:44,563 --> 00:17:47,648
大多数时候，我在监狱里与罪犯打交道。  
Mostly, in the prison, I work with criminals.

276
00:17:47,816 --> 00:17:51,694
所以我的看法可能略有偏差。
So my perception is slightly skewed.

277
00:17:51,904 --> 00:17:55,239
我认为肯定有蒙面英雄……
I think certainly there are masked heroes...

278
00:17:55,407 --> 00:17:58,826
……和超人类，比如曼哈顿博士……
...and superhumans, like Dr. Manhattan...

279
00:17:58,994 --> 00:18:00,995
……他们只想做好事。
...that just want to do good.

280
00:18:01,163 --> 00:18:05,958
我认为还有一些人不过是罪犯……
I think there are others that are nothing more than criminals...

281
00:18:06,126 --> 00:18:08,669
……他们以此为手段……
...who used this as a means...

282
00:18:08,837 --> 00:18:13,174
……来为自己的暴力倾向辩护。
...to justify their violent tendencies.

283
00:18:13,342 --> 00:18:19,305
真正构成实际威胁的蒙面英雄……
The only masked heroes that pose an actual threat...

284
00:18:19,807 --> 00:18:24,268
……是那些相对少数的边缘反社会者……
...are the relatively few borderline sociopaths...

285
00:18:24,436 --> 00:18:27,855
……他们真心相信自己是在行善。
...that actually believe that they are doing good.

286
00:18:28,023 --> 00:18:29,899
在那面具之下……
Beneath that mask...

287
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:33,653
……他们就像你我一样……
...they're just like you and me...

288
00:18:34,154 --> 00:18:38,407
……有希望和欲望，有恐惧……
...with hopes and desires, fears...

289
00:18:38,575 --> 00:18:40,910
……有爱。
...love.

290
00:18:41,870 --> 00:18:44,330
我希望有一天……
I hope that one day...

291
00:18:44,498 --> 00:18:49,502
……我能为这些蒙面英雄中的一位做心理分析。
...l can psychoanalyze one of these masked heroes.

292
00:18:50,045 --> 00:18:51,879
那会很有意思。
That would be something.

293
00:18:52,714 --> 00:18:54,799
如今看来那似乎是一个逝去的时代。
It seems a bygone era to us now.

294
00:18:54,967 --> 00:18:57,301
喧嚣的四十年代，令人陶醉的日子。
The heady days of the roaring '40s.

295
00:18:57,469 --> 00:19:00,721
人们渴望分心，渴求戏剧性的刺激。
People were eager for distraction, hungry for a fix of drama.

296
00:19:00,889 --> 00:19:04,058
还有什么比一群自封的超级英雄……
What better than a group of self-designed superheroes...

297
00:19:04,226 --> 00:19:07,562
……上演一场夸张的街头犯罪打击戏剧更好的呢？
...to act out an exaggerated street theater of crime fighting.

298
00:19:07,729 --> 00:19:10,898
在一个充斥着超级反派的世界里……
And in a world populated by supervillains...

299
00:19:11,066 --> 00:19:12,692
……何乐而不为呢？
...why not?

300
00:19:12,860 --> 00:19:15,736
有臭名昭著的神秘法师莫洛克……
There was the notorious Moloch the Mystic...

301
00:19:15,904 --> 00:19:21,242
……利用魔术表演的杂耍新奇感来掩饰他单枪匹马的恐怖浪潮。
...using the sideshow novelty of the magic show to front his one-man wave of terror.

302
00:19:21,410 --> 00:19:24,912
当然，后来出现了像大人物这样的现代超级反派……
Later, of course, came modern supervillains like Big Figure...

303
00:19:25,080 --> 00:19:29,375
……这位身材矮小的犯罪大师如今正在市监狱服无期徒刑。
...the diminutive master criminal now serving a life sentence in the city jail.

304
00:19:36,258 --> 00:19:38,426
你以为我是威胁。
You think I'm the menace.

305
00:19:38,927 --> 00:19:42,430
我可不是那个戴面具的人。我没什么好隐瞒的。
I'm not the one wearing a mask. I got nothing to hide.

306
00:19:42,806 --> 00:19:45,808
那是什么样的人？戴面具？
What kind of person is that? Wear a mask?

307
00:19:48,896 --> 00:19:52,273
我是个受人尊敬的商人。
I'm a respectable businessman.

308
00:19:53,150 --> 00:19:55,610
卡尔佩珀：找到神秘法师莫洛克可不容易。
CULPEPER: It wasn't easy finding Moloch the Mystic.

309
00:19:55,777 --> 00:19:58,237
但话说回来，嗯，也没那么难。
But then again, well, it wasn't too difficult.

310
00:19:58,405 --> 00:20:02,450
你看，莫洛克，就像我们战后历史上许多臭名昭著的人物一样……
You see, Moloch, like so many infamous figures of our postwar past...

311
00:20:02,618 --> 00:20:04,911
……只是过上了平民生活。
...had simply gone into civilian life.

312
00:20:05,996 --> 00:20:07,413
莫洛克：那时我还年轻。
MOLOCH: I was a younger man then.

313
00:20:07,581 --> 00:20:09,248
我很叛逆。
I was rebellious.

314
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:13,794
就像你看到的这些帮派，结顶帮。
Like these gangs you see around, the Knot Tops.

315
00:20:13,962 --> 00:20:17,757
当你生活在一个有超人类权威人物的世界里……
When you live in a world with superhuman authority figures...

316
00:20:17,925 --> 00:20:20,676
……而你想反抗，你就必须进行更大规模的抗争。
...and you wanna rebel, you have to rebel on a larger scale.

317
00:20:20,844 --> 00:20:24,263
你得把事情升级，明白吗。
You have to escalate things, you see.

318
00:20:24,431 --> 00:20:26,224
所以……
So...

319
00:20:26,600 --> 00:20:30,186
……如果你在一个有超级英雄的世界里长大，而你想反抗……
...if you grow up in a world with superheroes and you wanna rebel...

320
00:20:30,354 --> 00:20:34,357
……你就必须成为超级反派。
...you have to become a supervillain.

321
00:20:36,652 --> 00:20:41,030
所以，是的，我认为没有超级英雄的社会会更好……
So, yeah, l think society is better off without the superheroes...

322
00:20:41,198 --> 00:20:46,744
……因为那也意味着不再需要任何超级反派。
...because that means there's no need for any supervillains either.

323
00:20:49,957 --> 00:20:51,707
梅森：谢谢。谢谢。
MASON: Thank you. Thanks.

324
00:20:53,293 --> 00:20:58,047
你知道，它并没有持续，哦，十年。
You know, it didn't last, oh, 1 0 years.

325
00:20:58,215 --> 00:21:02,927
当五十年代到来时，人们对蒙面冒险家的整体看法……
When the '50s came, the whole perception of costumed adventurers...

326
00:21:03,095 --> 00:21:06,013
……你知道，改变了，明白吗？
...you know, changed, you know?

327
00:21:06,348 --> 00:21:07,515
那是一种潮流，是的。
It was a fad, yeah.

328
00:21:07,683 --> 00:21:11,352
而潮流正在消退，我们也随之消逝。
And the fad was dying out and we were dying with it.

329
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:12,728
[轻笑]
[CHUCKLES]

330
00:21:14,022 --> 00:21:15,606
莎莉……
Sally...

331
00:21:15,774 --> 00:21:17,984
……嗯，她怀孕了，然后离开了。
...well, she got pregnant and she left.

332
00:21:18,527 --> 00:21:21,779
我们剩下的人，被迫在……
The rest of us, we were forced to testify...

333
00:21:21,947 --> 00:21:24,365
……众议院非美活动调查委员会前作证。
...before the House Un-American Activities Committee.

334
00:21:24,533 --> 00:21:26,033
那是一场政治迫害。
It was a witch hunt.

335
00:21:26,201 --> 00:21:30,579
我们都被迫向其中一位代表……
We were all forced to reveal our identities...

336
00:21:30,747 --> 00:21:33,165
……透露了我们的真实身份。
...to one of its representatives.

337
00:21:33,333 --> 00:21:36,210
我是来自民兵组织的首都队长。
I am Captain Metropolis from the Minutemen.

338
00:21:36,378 --> 00:21:38,296
梅森：现在，幸运的是，由于首都队长……
MASON: Now, luckily, with Captain Metropolis...

339
00:21:38,463 --> 00:21:40,589
……拥有如此出色的军事记录……
...having such an outstanding military record...

340
00:21:40,757 --> 00:21:42,883
……再加上我自己在警察部门的服务……
...and with my own service in the police force...

341
00:21:43,051 --> 00:21:46,721
……我们俩或多或少都立刻摆脱了嫌疑。
...we both were more or less cleared of suspicion right away.

342
00:21:48,056 --> 00:21:52,476
飞蛾侠遇到了更多困难，主要是因为他那些左翼朋友……
Mothman met with more difficulty, mostly because of the left-wing friends...

343
00:21:52,644 --> 00:21:56,022
那是他在学生时代培养起来的。
...that he'd cultivated during his student days.

344
00:21:56,231 --> 00:21:57,898
如今他终于洗清了冤屈……
Now, he's eventually cleared...

345
00:21:58,066 --> 00:22:02,570
但调查过程如此漫长且残酷……
...but the investigations, they were so lengthy and so ruthless...

346
00:22:02,738 --> 00:22:05,406
以至于我认为他所承受的压力……
...that l think that the pressure he was under...

347
00:22:05,574 --> 00:22:07,783
加剧了他的酗酒问题……
...it exacerbated his drinking problem...

348
00:22:07,951 --> 00:22:11,996
并最终导致了他的精神崩溃。
...and it caused his eventual mental breakdown.

349
00:22:19,212 --> 00:22:21,422
兜帽判官……
Hooded Justice...

350
00:22:21,590 --> 00:22:22,923
拒绝作证……
...refused to testify...

351
00:22:23,091 --> 00:22:27,261
理由是他不准备向任何人透露自己的真实身份。
...on the grounds that he was not prepared to reveal his true identity to anybody.

352
00:22:27,429 --> 00:22:29,555
而当他们逼迫他时……
And when they pressed him...

353
00:22:30,182 --> 00:22:31,974
他便消失了。
...he disappeared.

354
00:22:32,476 --> 00:22:34,769
为此我十分敬重他。
And l really respect him for that.

355
00:22:35,437 --> 00:22:37,313
正是因为他，我才成为了夜枭……
He was the reason I became the Nite Owl...

356
00:22:37,481 --> 00:22:43,277
而时至今日，我仍不知面具后的他究竟是谁。
...and l don't know to this day who he was behind that mask.

357
00:22:43,445 --> 00:22:44,528
这难道不令人感慨吗？
Isn't that something?

358
00:22:44,696 --> 00:22:46,155
[轻笑]
[CHUCKLES]

359
00:22:46,323 --> 00:22:49,950
我了解到你离开民兵组织是因为怀孕了。
I understand that you wanted to leave the Minutemen because you got pregnant.

360
00:22:50,118 --> 00:22:52,119
是这个原因吗？是否还有其他理由……
Is that the reason? Was there any other reasons...

361
00:22:52,287 --> 00:22:55,289
让你从民兵组织退役？
...that you retired from the Minutemen?

362
00:22:56,500 --> 00:22:58,667
朱庇特：你知道，有时候只是到了该向前看的时候。
JUPITER: You know, sometimes it's just time to move on.

363
00:22:58,835 --> 00:23:02,254
我想如果没有怀孕，我可能会待得更久一些。
I think I would've stayed longer, had l not gotten pregnant.

364
00:23:02,422 --> 00:23:06,801
但事实是——你知道，生活总会给你一些小小的提示，告诉你何时该退出。
But it was-- You know, life gives you those little signs of when to take the door out.

365
00:23:06,968 --> 00:23:08,886
而那次似乎就是那个时机。
And that seemed to be the one.

366
00:23:09,054 --> 00:23:13,724
在他的传记中，霍利斯声称你曾遭到喜剧演员的性侵。
In his biography, Hollis alleged that you were sexually assaulted by The Comedian.

367
00:23:13,892 --> 00:23:16,185
但你对此从未发表过任何言论。
Yet you've never said anything about this.

368
00:23:16,645 --> 00:23:18,145
嗯。
Hmm.

369
00:23:19,481 --> 00:23:22,274
那么，我为什么要打破一辈子的习惯呢，对吧？
Well, why should l break a lifetime's habit now, right?

370
00:23:22,442 --> 00:23:23,609
[轻笑]
[CHUCKLES]

371
00:23:23,777 --> 00:23:29,031
作为记者，我理解你的提问，但，是的，这件事——
I can't blame you for asking as a reporter, but, yes, it's--

372
00:23:29,199 --> 00:23:30,241
无可奉告。
No comment.

373
00:23:30,409 --> 00:23:36,205
莎莉·朱庇特和喜剧演员之间的事件……
How much did the incident between Sally Jupiter and The Comedian...

374
00:23:36,373 --> 00:23:38,374
……对你决定摘下面具有多大影响？
...affect your decision to hang up the mask?

375
00:23:38,959 --> 00:23:42,795
嗯，那确实有很大关系，是的。
Well, that had lot to do with it, yeah.

376
00:23:44,673 --> 00:23:47,550
我想一旦你意识到你的某些队友……
I think once you realize that some of your teammates...

377
00:23:47,717 --> 00:23:50,344
……和你追捕的罪犯一样堕落……
...are just as depraved...

378
00:23:50,512 --> 00:23:55,599
……一样扭曲……
...and twisted as the criminals you're going after....

379
00:23:57,310 --> 00:23:59,019
是的。
Yeah.

380
00:23:59,521 --> 00:24:02,189
那是我退出的主要原因。
That had a lot to do with why I quit.

381
00:24:02,357 --> 00:24:04,400
那个传闻并非事实。
There's no truth to that rumor.

382
00:24:04,568 --> 00:24:06,360
如果真发生了那样的事……
If something like that had happened...

383
00:24:06,528 --> 00:24:12,158
……难道你不认为我会建议莎莉提起刑事诉讼吗？
...don't you think I would have advised Sally to have pressed criminal charges?

384
00:24:12,325 --> 00:24:14,910
她是我最好的客户。是我最大的收入来源。
She was my best client. My biggest earner.

385
00:24:15,454 --> 00:24:18,539
我绝不会让那样的事逍遥法外。
I would never allow something like that to go unpunished.

386
00:24:18,707 --> 00:24:20,666
这不过是哗众取宠罢了。
It's nothing more than sensationalism.

387
00:24:21,209 --> 00:24:22,751
自我炒作而已。
Self-promotion.

388
00:24:22,919 --> 00:24:25,504
霍利斯·梅森想多卖几本书。
Hollis Mason wants to sell more books.

389
00:24:25,672 --> 00:24:28,090
卡尔佩珀：笑匠拒绝发表评论。
CULPEPER: The Comedian declined to comment.

390
00:24:28,258 --> 00:24:32,219
把那玩意儿从我面前拿开，否则我就把雪茄按在你眼睛里。
Get that thing out of my face before l put my cigar out in your eye.

391
00:24:33,430 --> 00:24:35,890
《面罩之下》是本精彩绝伦的书。
Under the Hood is a fantastic book.

392
00:24:36,057 --> 00:24:38,184
要知道，他也是我的顾客之一。
You know, he's one of my customers, you know.

393
00:24:38,351 --> 00:24:40,352
我经常能见到他。
I see him all the time.

394
00:24:40,687 --> 00:24:45,316
关于超级英雄这事儿很有意思，要知道，那条界限非常微妙。
It's funny about this superhero thing, you know, it's a very fine line.

395
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:47,443
当你遇到像夜枭这样的人……
And when you got somebody like the Nite Owl...

396
00:24:47,611 --> 00:24:51,822
他是典型的超级英雄，因为在外人看来这家伙……
...who is your quintessential superhero, because outside you get this guy...

397
00:24:51,990 --> 00:24:54,533
穿着戏服整天打打杀杀轰轰烈烈……
...who dresses up and does all the kaboom-kabang stuff...

398
00:24:54,701 --> 00:24:57,453
但内里他其实是个警察。
...but inside he's a cop.

399
00:24:57,621 --> 00:25:00,831
所以他是个明辨是非的人。明白我的意思吗？
So he's a guy who knows what's true blue. You know what l mean?

400
00:25:00,999 --> 00:25:03,209
他不搞那些花里胡哨的名堂。
He's not into these kind of artsy-fartsy things.

401
00:25:03,376 --> 00:25:05,127
他是个了不起的人。
He's a great man.

402
00:25:05,670 --> 00:25:07,087
所以……
So...

403
00:25:07,255 --> 00:25:08,756
我也说不清。
...l don't know.

404
00:25:08,924 --> 00:25:14,803
很难判断这些蒙面英雄到底是好是坏……
Hard to say whether these masked-hero types are a good or a bad thing...

405
00:25:14,971 --> 00:25:18,224
要知道，归根结底是这样。
...you know, in the final analysis.

406
00:25:18,391 --> 00:25:21,560
值得注意的是早在1975年……
It's interesting to note that back in 1 975...

407
00:25:21,728 --> 00:25:24,647
人们对这类存在仍存在巨大分歧……
...people were still very much divided as to whether or not...

408
00:25:24,814 --> 00:25:29,443
所谓的蒙面义警对社会究竟有益还是有害。
...the so-called costumed adventurers were a benefit or a detriment to society.

409
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:31,779
鉴于本次访谈播出后发生的事件……
Given the events after this interview aired...

410
00:25:31,947 --> 00:25:35,324
……或许霍利斯·梅森的退休来得正是时候。
...perhaps Hollis Mason's retirement came at the perfect time.

411
00:25:35,492 --> 00:25:39,286
广告之后我们将继续聆听霍利斯·梅森的讲述。
We'll hear more from Hollis Mason after this commercial break.

412
00:25:40,622 --> 00:25:42,456
播音员：为何如此多人选择洁厕灵……
ANNOUNCER: Why do so many choose Sani-Flush...

413
00:25:42,624 --> 00:25:45,125
……而非其他主流马桶清洁剂？
...instead of the other leading bathroom-bowl cleaner?

414
00:25:45,293 --> 00:25:46,835
洁厕灵拥有超凡效力。
Sani-Flush has extra power.

415
00:25:47,003 --> 00:25:51,048
清洁马桶内壁，彻底洗净弯道。
Cleans inside the bowl and cleans right round the bend.

416
00:25:51,675 --> 00:25:54,301
延时镜头显示，洁厕灵凭借其超凡效力……
Time-lapse shows Sani-Flush, with its extra power...

417
00:25:54,469 --> 00:25:56,345
……能清除锈渍与沉积物……
...cleans away rust stains and deposits...

418
00:25:56,513 --> 00:25:58,931
……深入马桶内壁，彻底洗净弯道。
...inside the bowl and right round the bend.

419
00:25:59,099 --> 00:26:01,976
洁厕灵，拥有灭杀数百万细菌的强大功效。
Sani-Flush, with the power to kill germs by the millions.

420
00:26:02,143 --> 00:26:06,063
洁厕灵。清洁马桶内壁，彻底洗净弯道。
Sani-Flush. Cleans inside the bowl and cleans right round the bend.

421
00:26:06,231 --> 00:26:08,899
选择洁厕灵，粉剂或液体均可。
Get Sani-Flush, powder or liquid.

422
00:26:10,986 --> 00:26:13,862
现在继续我对霍利斯·梅森的访谈。
Continuing now with my interview of Hollis Mason.

423
00:26:14,030 --> 00:26:16,240
我们正在讨论蒙面义警的话题。
We're talking about costumed adventurers.

424
00:26:16,408 --> 00:26:19,159
他被称为世界第八大奇迹。
He's been called the Eighth Wonder of the World.

425
00:26:19,327 --> 00:26:22,037
我们的国家瑰宝。我们最伟大的希望。
Our national treasure. Our greatest hope.

426
00:26:22,205 --> 00:26:25,374
但曼哈顿博士也被视为自然界的异类。
But Dr. Manhattan is also viewed as a freak of nature.

427
00:26:25,542 --> 00:26:31,046
他的力量如此强大，不仅令敌人恐惧，也让我们自己心生畏惧。  
His power is so great as to illicit fear not only in our enemies but in ourselves.

428
00:26:31,214 --> 00:26:34,383
在他成为今日这般散发蓝光的超能存在之前……  
Before he was the radiating blue superbeing he is today...

429
00:26:34,551 --> 00:26:38,304
……他曾是乔恩·奥斯特曼，物理学家，钟表匠之子。  
...he was Jon Osterman, physicist, son of a watchmaker.

430
00:26:38,471 --> 00:26:43,183
一个拥有友情、爱情和普通家庭观念的人。  
A man with friendships, loves, common family values.

431
00:26:43,351 --> 00:26:45,686
他的一位朋友，实际上也是同事……  
One of his friends and, in fact, colleagues...

432
00:26:45,854 --> 00:26:48,480
……至今仍与曼哈顿博士共事……  
...who continues to work with Dr. Manhattan today...

433
00:26:48,648 --> 00:26:51,233
……本身就是一位备受尊敬的物理学家……  
...is an esteemed physicist in his own right...

434
00:26:51,401 --> 00:26:52,526
……沃利·韦弗。  
...Wally Weaver.

435
00:26:52,694 --> 00:26:55,362
我们前往韦弗的实验室，进行了如下对话。  
We went to Weaver's lab and had the following conversation.

436
00:26:55,530 --> 00:26:58,490
嗯，我认为……  
Well, l think...

437
00:26:58,700 --> 00:27:00,909
……各类英雄都是好事。  
...heroes of all kinds are a good thing.

438
00:27:01,077 --> 00:27:05,539
我指的是我们武装部队中勇敢的男女军人。  
And l'm talking about the brave men and women of our Armed Forces.

439
00:27:05,707 --> 00:27:09,335
我指的是警察和消防员。  
I'm talking about the policemen and the firefighters.

440
00:27:09,502 --> 00:27:14,840
我指的是科学家和医生。还有，呃……  
I'm talking about the scientists and the doctors. And, uh....

441
00:27:15,216 --> 00:27:18,052
是的，我也会把蒙面英雄……  
Yeah, l'd include masked heroes...

442
00:27:18,219 --> 00:27:20,721
……归入那类对社会有益的人群中。  
...in that group that's a benefit to society too.

443
00:27:20,889 --> 00:27:22,431
但乔恩——  
Jon is--

444
00:27:22,599 --> 00:27:26,143
抱歉，曼哈顿博士……  
I'm sorry. Dr. Manhattan...

445
00:27:26,561 --> 00:27:28,771
……完全是另一回事。  
...is something else entirely.

446
00:27:29,606 --> 00:27:35,486
我正在写一本书，讲述他如何永远改变了地缘政治格局……  
I'm writing a book about how he's changed the geopolitical landscape forever...

447
00:27:36,154 --> 00:27:39,907
……从根本上重塑了……的概念。
...essentially making the very idea...

448
00:27:40,075 --> 00:27:42,993
...使得战争过时了。
...of war obsolete.

449
00:27:44,704 --> 00:27:50,292
梅森：你知道，第一反应是完全难以置信。
MASON: You know, the first thing was absolute disbelief.

450
00:27:50,460 --> 00:27:53,087
当然，正如你所知，也有狂喜。
Well, of course, as you know, there was elation too.

451
00:27:53,254 --> 00:27:56,757
我的意思是，就像圣诞老人活生生地、生机勃勃地存在。
I mean, it was like Santa Claus was alive and thriving.

452
00:27:56,925 --> 00:27:59,176
但恐惧……
But the fear....

453
00:28:00,220 --> 00:28:03,597
那是一种可怕的恐惧……
It was a terrible fear...

454
00:28:03,765 --> 00:28:07,726
……以及一种直击你核心的不确定性。
...and an uncertainty that went right to your core.

455
00:28:07,894 --> 00:28:10,270
我当然能理解一辆旧车的感觉……
I certainly understood how an old car feels...

456
00:28:10,438 --> 00:28:13,440
……当它看到一辆新车，一个新车型驶出来时。
...when it sees a new car, a new model come rolling out.

457
00:28:13,608 --> 00:28:15,109
[轻笑]
[CHUCKLES]

458
00:28:15,735 --> 00:28:17,361
但这不止如此。
But it was more than that.

459
00:28:17,529 --> 00:28:23,951
你知道，我想我可以用三个字来概括那种感觉，真的。那就是：
You know, I think I can boil the feeling down to three words, really. lt's:

460
00:28:24,119 --> 00:28:26,286
我们被取代了。
We've been replaced.

461
00:28:26,454 --> 00:28:29,707
我指的不只是那些戴面具的冒险家。
And l don't just mean the masked adventurers.

462
00:28:29,874 --> 00:28:33,043
我指的是，人类。
I mean, humanity.

463
00:28:33,962 --> 00:28:35,879
我们被取代了。
We've been replaced.

464
00:28:39,134 --> 00:28:42,428
霍利斯总是有戏剧性的天赋。
Hollis always did have a flair for the dramatic.

465
00:28:42,595 --> 00:28:45,639
毫无疑问，这对我们所有人来说都是一个绝对的震惊。
There is no doubt that it was an absolute shock to all of us.

466
00:28:45,807 --> 00:28:48,642
像曼哈顿博士这样的存在能够存在的事实。
The fact that anything could exist like Dr. Manhattan.

467
00:28:48,810 --> 00:28:53,105
我的意思是，这对我们来说是超出概念范畴的东西。
I mean, this was something out of the realm of concept for us.

468
00:28:53,273 --> 00:28:56,150
但我们永远需要人性……
But we will always have a need for humanity...

469
00:28:56,317 --> 00:29:01,822
……无论我们在技术上如何扩展和成长，这是——
...and as much as we expand and grow technologically, it's--

470
00:29:01,990 --> 00:29:04,116
我们仍然需要人类的接触，你知道吗？
We still need human contact, you know?

471
00:29:04,743 --> 00:29:07,911
人们总是误解我关于乔恩的言论。  
People have always misinterpreted what I said about Jon.

472
00:29:08,455 --> 00:29:13,917
我并非将他比作神明。  
I wasn't comparing him to God. I wasn't saying he was a god.

473
00:29:14,085 --> 00:29:15,669
也未曾宣称他是神。  
I just--

474
00:29:16,796 --> 00:29:19,173
我只是——  
Just wish I wouldn't have ever said that.

475
00:29:19,549 --> 00:29:22,843
只是希望自己从未说过那些话。  
Bottom line is this: Jon is still Jon.

476
00:29:23,470 --> 00:29:25,429
归根结底：乔恩依然是乔恩。  
At his core...

477
00:29:26,473 --> 00:29:28,307
在他的本质里……  
...he's still a man.

478
00:29:29,434 --> 00:29:34,396
……他仍是凡人。  
Well, take what I said about supervillains being a direct response...

479
00:29:34,564 --> 00:29:36,523
那么，将我关于超级反派是直接回应……  
...to the appearance of superheroes...

480
00:29:36,691 --> 00:29:40,068
……超级英雄出现的言论……  
...and apply that to the current scenario.

481
00:29:40,236 --> 00:29:44,281
……套用到当前局势中。  
If you have a being that can destroy...

482
00:29:44,449 --> 00:29:46,033
若存在一个能凭一念之间……  
...with a single thought...

483
00:29:46,201 --> 00:29:48,410
……摧毁一切的存在……  
...then the terrifying thing is that there is...

484
00:29:48,578 --> 00:29:53,874
那么可怕之处在于……  
...or there soon will be, a counterpoint or an adversary to that being.

485
00:29:54,042 --> 00:29:59,046
……很快就会出现与之抗衡的对立者或敌手。  
The universe has a way of finding its own equilibrium, its own level.

486
00:30:00,465 --> 00:30:06,136
宇宙自有其寻找平衡与稳定之道。  
What worries me is that Dr. Manhattan's nemesis will be arriving soon.

487
00:30:10,767 --> 00:30:13,310
令我担忧的是，曼哈顿博士的宿敌即将到来。  
Of course, some of these masked adventurers...

488
00:30:13,478 --> 00:30:16,063
当然，有些蒙面冒险家……  
...never stopped practicing their unique craft.

489
00:30:16,231 --> 00:30:20,150
……从未停止磨练他们独特的技艺。  
Eventually time moved forward to a point where their presence was again welcomed...

490
00:30:20,318 --> 00:30:22,611
时光流转至某一刻，他们的存在再次被接纳……  
...and some would say sorely needed.

491
00:30:23,196 --> 00:30:25,239
……甚至有人会说已迫在眉睫。  
Big city streets festered with violence...

492
00:30:25,406 --> 00:30:27,574
恐吓与犯罪猖獗。
...intimidation and rampant crime.

493
00:30:27,742 --> 00:30:31,620
这正是新型蒙面英雄诞生的绝佳土壤。
A perfect environment for a new breed of masked hero to emerge.

494
00:30:31,788 --> 00:30:34,081
当然，我指的是守望者。
Of course, I speak of the Watchmen.

495
00:30:34,624 --> 00:30:38,752
如今，随着冷战升级和真正超级存在的介入…
Now, with the Cold War escalating and the presence of a truly super being...

496
00:30:38,920 --> 00:30:41,046
…成为我们国防的前沿力量…
...at the forefront of our national defense...

497
00:30:41,214 --> 00:30:45,217
…一种日益增长的恐惧与不安似乎正渗透进民众之中。
...a growing fear and restlessness seems to permeate the population.

498
00:30:45,885 --> 00:30:48,554
只是这一次，恐惧的对象并非罪犯…
Only this time, the fear is not of the criminals...

499
00:30:48,721 --> 00:30:50,764
…而是打击犯罪者本身。
...but of the crime fighters themselves.

500
00:30:50,932 --> 00:30:54,393
基恩参议员无疑认为时机已到…
Senator Keene surely thinks that the time has come to put an end...

501
00:30:54,561 --> 00:30:55,936
…该终结蒙面义警的行为了。
...to masked adventuring.

502
00:30:56,104 --> 00:31:00,774
他提出的新法律将有效束缚这些蒙面英雄的羽翼…
His suggested new laws would effectively clip the wings of these costumed heroes...

503
00:31:00,942 --> 00:31:02,568
…迫使他们摘下自己的面具…
...making them hang up their masks...

504
00:31:02,735 --> 00:31:06,613
…阻止他们在我们美好的街道上行使私刑正义。
...and preventing them from practicing vigilante justice in our fair streets.

505
00:31:07,115 --> 00:31:10,951
基恩参议员是个投机主义的…
Senator Keene is an opportunistic...

506
00:31:12,328 --> 00:31:14,162
…空洞符号。
...cipher.

507
00:31:14,330 --> 00:31:16,874
他根本不明白自己在说什么。
He has no idea what he's talking about.

508
00:31:17,041 --> 00:31:19,543
真正的问题在于警察部门。
The real problem are the police departments.

509
00:31:19,711 --> 00:31:24,506
如果他们能多借鉴一些这些蒙面英雄的特质…
If they would take a little bit more of what these masked heroes have...

510
00:31:24,674 --> 00:31:27,593
…我们就不需要基恩参议员这样的人了…
...then we wouldn't need people like Senator Keene...

511
00:31:27,760 --> 00:31:29,219
...首先是在参议院。
...in the Senate in the first place.

512
00:31:30,471 --> 00:31:32,264
我对基恩参议员有何看法？
What do I think about Senator Keene?

513
00:31:32,432 --> 00:31:34,474
听着，我每天都在这里工作。
Listen, l work down here every day.

514
00:31:34,642 --> 00:31:37,978
每当我遇到麻烦，每当有人在这里痛斥我...
Whenever I'm in trouble, whenever somebody's down here beating me up...

515
00:31:38,146 --> 00:31:40,856
...而我大声呼救时，我不在乎是谁来救我的命。
...and l yell for help, l don't care who comes to save my butt.

516
00:31:41,024 --> 00:31:44,484
我不在乎是超级英雄，也不在乎是警察。
I don't care if it's a superhero. I don't care if it's a cop.

517
00:31:44,652 --> 00:31:47,821
只要有人在我喊"救命"时出现就行。
As long as somebody comes when l'm yelling "help."

518
00:31:48,239 --> 00:31:49,323
你明白吗？
You understand?

519
00:31:49,490 --> 00:31:51,700
人们...
People have...

520
00:31:51,993 --> 00:31:54,328
...需要...
...a need for...

521
00:31:54,495 --> 00:31:56,496
...一位日常英雄。
...an everyday hero.

522
00:31:56,873 --> 00:31:59,166
无论是否蒙面。
Masked or otherwise.

523
00:31:59,334 --> 00:32:01,168
而且，呃...
And, uh...

524
00:32:03,296 --> 00:32:07,424
...那些明辨是非的人...
...people who know right from wrong...

525
00:32:07,592 --> 00:32:11,261
...永远都会是需要的。
...will always be in demand.

526
00:32:24,734 --> 00:32:29,363
那么此刻我想稍微谈点个人话题。
So l want to get a little personal here for the moment.

527
00:32:29,572 --> 00:32:31,073
你从未结婚。这是为什么？
You never married. Why is that?

528
00:32:33,826 --> 00:32:36,870
-嗯... -谢谢。
-Um.... -Thank you.

529
00:32:37,038 --> 00:32:40,582
我想，如果非要找一个我从未结婚的理由...
Well, l suppose if there's any one reason why l never got married...

530
00:32:40,750 --> 00:32:42,292
...那是因为...
...it was because...

531
00:32:43,461 --> 00:32:47,255
...嗯，莎莉·朱庇特已经名花有主了。
...well, Sally Jupiter was taken.

532
00:32:47,423 --> 00:32:49,383
我认为...
I don't think...

533
00:32:49,550 --> 00:32:52,552
...我对她有好感，这算不上什么大秘密。
...it's any great secret that I had a thing for her.

534
00:32:52,720 --> 00:32:54,888
当时一半的男性都对她有好感。
Half the male population did.

535
00:32:55,056 --> 00:32:59,226
等我终于鼓起勇气，想约她正式出去约会时...
By the time l'd rustled up the courage to ask her out on a proper date...

536
00:32:59,894 --> 00:33:01,937
...她已经嫁给了她的经纪人。
...she was already married to her manager.

537
00:33:02,522 --> 00:33:04,189
[轻笑]
[CHUCKLES]

538
00:33:05,566 --> 00:33:07,901
说起来还挺有趣的。
It's kind of funny when you think of it.

539
00:33:08,236 --> 00:33:13,448
我每天扮成猫头鹰出生入死……
I dress up as an owl and risk my life on a daily basis...

540
00:33:14,033 --> 00:33:17,911
……但到了约女孩出来的时候……
...but when it came to asking a girl out...

541
00:33:18,079 --> 00:33:20,664
……我却束手无策。
...it was more than l could manage.

542
00:33:20,873 --> 00:33:25,210
可悲的是，我觉得我们的婚姻从一开始就注定了失败。
Sadly, I think our marriage was doomed from the start.

543
00:33:25,378 --> 00:33:29,798
我在莎莉生活中的职业身份让我很难成为一个好丈夫。
My professional position in Sally's life made it very difficult to be a good husband.

544
00:33:29,966 --> 00:33:31,800
作为她的经纪人，我的工作……
It was my job as her manager...

545
00:33:31,968 --> 00:33:35,303
……不仅是接受男人被她吸引的事实……
...to not only accept the fact that men were attracted to her...

546
00:33:35,471 --> 00:33:37,931
……还要利用这种吸引力……
...but to build on that attraction...

547
00:33:38,891 --> 00:33:41,059
……从中牟利。
...to prey upon it.

548
00:33:47,817 --> 00:33:49,443
霍利斯对你来说非常重要。
Hollis was very important to you.

549
00:33:49,610 --> 00:33:51,695
他是你生命中非常重要的人，对吗？
He was a very important person in your life, correct?

550
00:33:51,863 --> 00:33:52,904
毫无疑问。
Absolutely.

551
00:33:53,072 --> 00:33:56,116
-你们现在还有联系吗？-有的，有的。
-You stay in contact with each other today? -We do. We do.

552
00:33:56,284 --> 00:33:58,618
不过我得说，联系不如我希望的那么频繁。
Not as much as l would like, I must say.

553
00:33:58,786 --> 00:34:01,079
你知道，人生轨迹总会走向不同的方向……
You know, your life takes you in different directions...

554
00:34:01,247 --> 00:34:04,666
……但那确实是一段不可思议的、梦幻般的时光……
...but that was really a magical, magical time...

555
00:34:04,834 --> 00:34:08,336
……我们相聚时总爱聊起那些旧日往事。
...and we do like to talk about the old times when we get together.

556
00:34:08,963 --> 00:34:10,839
你知道吗，我觉得——
You know, I think--

557
00:34:11,299 --> 00:34:13,717
我觉得我心里还藏着某种……
I think I still have some kind of...

558
00:34:13,885 --> 00:34:16,803
……不成熟的念头……
...half-baked idea that...

559
00:34:17,305 --> 00:34:21,475
……关于夜枭和，呃……
...Nite Owl and, uh...

560
00:34:22,143 --> 00:34:26,313
丝鬼和夜枭总有一天会在一起的。
...Silk Spectre are gonna end up together one day.

561
00:34:34,697 --> 00:34:36,031
嗯。
Hm.

562
00:34:37,784 --> 00:34:40,160
当初我们采访霍利斯·梅森时...
When we originally spoke with Hollis Mason...

563
00:34:40,328 --> 00:34:43,371
...他相信他作为夜枭开创的传承...
...he believed that the legacy he'd begun as the Nite Owl...

564
00:34:43,539 --> 00:34:45,957
...以及蒙面英雄群体的其他成员...
...along with other members of the masked-hero community...

565
00:34:46,125 --> 00:34:48,168
...将在未来岁月中延续下去。
...would live on for years to come.

566
00:34:48,336 --> 00:34:51,797
他当时不可能知道自己错得多么离谱。
He could not have known how wrong he was.

567
00:34:55,134 --> 00:34:59,638
本期节目带我们怀旧回顾了这个国家历史上一个多彩的时代...
This has been a nostalgic look back at a colorful time in this nation's past...

568
00:34:59,806 --> 00:35:02,849
...那时我们曾向身着卡通服装的浮夸英雄...
...when we turned to flamboyant heroes with cartoonish outfits...

569
00:35:03,017 --> 00:35:04,392
...寻求道德指引。
...for our moral outlook.

570
00:35:04,560 --> 00:35:06,978
在我们如今生活的后基恩法案时代...
In the post-Keene Act world we now live in...

571
00:35:07,146 --> 00:35:09,689
...蒙面英雄已如同霍利斯·梅森在车库里修理的那些...
...the masked heroes are as outdated and irrelevant...

572
00:35:09,857 --> 00:35:13,735
...破旧报废车辆般过时且无关紧要。
...as the old beat-up wrecks that Hollis Mason works on in his garage.

573
00:35:13,903 --> 00:35:17,906
希望这次对制服冒险者历史的回顾...
We hope that you have found this look back at the history of costumed adventurers...

574
00:35:18,074 --> 00:35:20,534
...能带给各位启迪与新知。
...both enlightening and informative.

575
00:35:20,701 --> 00:35:23,578
我是《卡尔佩珀一分钟》的拉里·卡尔佩珀。
I'm Larry Culpeper for The Culpeper Minute.

576
00:37:31,916 --> 00:37:33,917
[英文字幕]
[ENGLISH SDH]

